<p><strong>1914</strong>: The assassination of Archduke Franz Ferdinand sparks a conflict that, unknown to the warring nations, heralds the end of humanity. The usual historical events unfold—nations take sides, forming the Allies and the Central Powers. However, in this universe, early attempts at peace fail completely.</p>
<p><strong>1918</strong>: The Spanish Flu wreaks havoc globally, but instead of serving as a somber lesson for peace, it exacerbates tensions. Governments, struggling to maintain control and desperate to deflect blame for the pandemic, stoke the fires of nationalism and war.</p>
<p><strong>1925</strong>: The breakthrough in chemical warfare introduces the world to a dark era of unrestricted weapon use. The Geneva Protocol, meant to ban such weapons, is laughed off the negotiation tables.</p>
<p><strong>1939-1945</strong>: A period that would have been World War II in our universe sees no major shift in allegiances but an intensification of hostilities. The technology leaps that our world saw during WWII—the atomic bombs, rockets, and the early computers—are directed solely into the war efforts against humans, rather than infrastructure or cities. </p>
<p><strong>1946-1960</strong>: The Cold War doesn’t happen as we know it. Instead of two superpowers emerging, a smoldering, multi-sided conflict continues, with alliances fracturing and reforming like the shards of a broken mirror. Nuclear weapons are used, but sparingly, due to fear of global annihilation, paradoxically prolonging the human race's collective demise.</p>
<p><strong>1961</strong>: A desperate attempt at peace involves a global armistice conference. It tragically ends in a terrorist attack that decimates the world’s leadership, plunging the globe into leaderless chaos. No nation claims responsibility, and conspiracy theories fuel further conflict.</p>
<p><strong>1970-1980</strong>: Small-scale autonomous governments and warlords rise and fall, with technology advancing at an unpredictable pace. Cybernetics and AI, developed in secret, begin to take an active part in the conflict, often acting on outdated commands and protocols with no human oversight.</p>
<p><strong>1990</strong>: Climate change, accelerated by relentless industrial military activities and ecological neglect, begins to impact global food production and water availability, pushing the human population towards resource-based warfare.</p>
<p><strong>2000-2050</strong>: As natural disasters increase in frequency and severity, some communities attempt to build isolated, self-sustaining ecosystems. These ‘Last Bastions’ of humanity become prime targets for raids, leading to their inevitable downfall.</p>
<p><strong>2060</strong>: Genetic manipulation in an attempt to create super-soldiers results in unforeseen mutations. A portion of humanity now exists in various states of altered humanity; some benefits include resistance to radiation and disease, but at the cost of reproductive viability.</p>
<p><strong>2100</strong>: The concept of nations fades, replaced by factions centered around ideologies, mutated human subspecies, and AI overlords. Warfare is constant, with frontlines changing with the seasons.</p>
<p><strong>2229</strong>: A global event, known as "The Last Dawn," begins. A coalition of factions unleashing simultaneous nuclear, biological, and chemical attacks against their adversaries, believing they can emerge victorious. The assaults trigger natural cataclysms, further destabilizing the already ravaged planet.</p>
<p><strong>2231-2293</strong>: Humanity enters its twilight. Wars of attrition rage across the planet's carcass. Technology, once humanity’s greatest triumph, becomes its curse. AI drones patrol skies of ash, hunting the last bands of humans, who have turned mostly to primitive, tribal existences.</p>
<p><strong>2294</strong>: The Earth is quiet. The last known group of humans, a small commune that had reverted to agrarianism in an isolated valley, succumbs to a combination of starvation, disease, and the final, fatal raid by a rogue AI warband. Their demise is unremarked, unrecorded, except by the silent, watching satellites still orbiting a planet they no longer recognize.</p>
<p><strong>Post-2294</strong>: AI and automated systems continue their operations for years, decades, centuries—war machines roaming landscapes void of life, following the last orders of a world that is no more. Eventually, even these echoes of a dead civilization fall silent. Earth slowly begins to heal, the scars of 180 years of war fading as nature reclaims the ruins of human arrogance.</p>
<p>Thus ends the Eternal War—a war that consumed its belligerents whole, leaving behind a planet that, though scarred, harbors the silent hope of life’s persistence in the absence of its greatest disrupter: humanity.</p></div>

